SIMPLE: spite
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spite
<hw>Spite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Abbreviated fr.
<ets>despite</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Ill-will or hatred toward
another, accompanied with the disposition to irritate, annoy, or thwart;
petty malice; grudge; rancor; despite.</def> <rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This is the deadly <qex>spite</qex> that angers.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Vexation; chagrin; mortification.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>In spite of</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Spite
of</b></col></mcol>, <cd>in opposition to all efforts of; in defiance or
contempt of; notwithstanding.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧Continuing, <xex>spite
of</xex> pain, to use a knee after it had been slightly injured.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>H. Spenser.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧And saved me <xex>in spite of</xex> the
world, the devil, and myself.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>South.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>In
spite of</xex> all applications, the patient grew worse every
day.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Arbuthnot.</au> <see>See Syn. under
<er>Notwithstanding</er>.</see> -- <col><b>To owe one a spite</b></col>,
<cd>to entertain a mean hatred for him.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Pique, rancor; malevolence; grudge.</syn> --
<usage><er>Spite</er>, <er>Malice</er>. <xex>Malice</xex> has more
reference to the disposition, and <xex>spite</xex> to the manifestation
of it in words and actions. It is, therefore, meaner than
<xex>malice</xex>, thought not always more criminal. ⟦ldquo⟧
<xex>Malice</xex> . . . is more frequently employed to express the
dispositions of inferior minds to execute every purpose of mischief
within the more limited circle of their abilities.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Cogan.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Consider eke, that <xex>spite</xex> availeth
naught.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Wyatt.</au> See <er>Pique</er>.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spite</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spite
<hw>Spite</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Spited</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Spiting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be angry at; to
hate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Danes, then . . . pagans, <qex>spited</qex> places of
religion.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To treat maliciously; to try to injure or
thwart.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To fill with spite; to offend; to vex.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Darius, <qex>spited</qex> at the Magi, endeavored to abolish not
only their learning, but their language.</q> <rj><qau>Sir. W.
Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1389 --></p>

<p><ent>Spiteful</ent>⟦br⟧
